Now Martial‚ addressing his fourth book, advises it to gain tlte approval of Apollinaris, and tells it, if condemned, to be off to the trunk-makers' :

The words are almost exactly those of Catullus ; the mean- ing is entirely different. There can be no stronger proof of ingrained familiarity than such unconscious imitation.

The following is a list of the passages in the Eclogues and Georgics which are most obviously imitated from the fifth book of Lucretius.

Lucr. v 8 deus ille fuit, deus, inclyte Memmi. Ecl. ν 64 deus, deus ille, Menalca.

Lucr. v 30 equi spirantes naribus ignem. Georg. ii 140 tauri spirantes naribus ignem. Lucr. ν 33 asper, acerba tuens.

Georg. iii 149 asper, acerba sonans.
